english:
  title: The Immortal Youths
  author: Guo Dong-sun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Since Fuxi ruled all under heaven, none has surpassed our Great Founder's Three Kingdoms. Those divine immortals upon distant Guasishan—are they not the Four Youths of our Moon City? Their windswept elegance flows through all ages, yet their craftsmanship finds renewal in our own court. Our ancestors delighted in this; harmony spreads above and below. Thus we celebrate.

    I have heard that ancient Silla, that old seat of glory, lies in the eastern corner where waters gather—a place bearing the spirit of primordial times, known as the Kingdom of Gentlemen. A purple egg descended from heaven; a divine dragon emerged from a sacred well. For a thousand years the Yellow River ran clear, and from Holy Bone and True Bone the succession passed down. Five hundred years saw the Youths bloom forth. Such immortals as Wonrang and Nanrang, those banished sages, wandered through sublime peaks seeking leisurely repose. Those who crossed thresholds to sit with them numbered in the ten thousands. In the Western Obscurity and Northern Heights they wandered as in dreams through the land of Huaxu; among clustered stones and singing sands they glimpsed the palaces of Penglai upon the sea. Not eaters of mere grain and rice were these, but truly beings of cloud and mist. When at last they ascended through nine transformations, who could witness their divine travels across the eight horizons? The peach blossoms and flowing waters fade into distance; though their true traces grow hard to find, the old customs of noble houses still endure. Heaven has not abandoned us.

    So our Great Founder, stirred to righteous courage in the twilight of Water's reign, established his vast foundation upon the ruins of Dongmyeong. His six meritorious ministers surpassed the Three Heroes of Xiaohao, Zhang Liang, and Han Xin. The Mandate he sought for ten thousand generations united Chen, Bian, and Mahan into one household. To answer the gracious gifts bestowed together by Heaven and Earth, he composed music wherein ruler and ministers delight in each other. From the Dragon Pillar he obtained Numinous Script, opened the Eight Rightnesses and closed the Eight Perversities. Consulting the Immortal Registry of Chicken Forest, above is the Eastern Moon, below the Western Moon. He decreed: "Let this law I have made become the ancient law; once each year let it be performed as custom." Thus he bequeathed it to his descendants, inscribed clearly in the histories.

    I humbly reflect: the Lord on High stands in the prime of spring and autumn, his sacred teachings ascending daily. He inherits the boundless merit and virtue of his ancestors, yet takes his morning repast late and dons his night robes early, never wearying in governance. His undertakings shine forth in brilliant splendor. He establishes great peace for the realm—one might release the oxen and call back the horses. The bells and drums sound their own joy, yet he does not succumb to wine and music. He shares delight with his people, adjusting rites to the seasons. In this season of mid-winter, he revives the ancient ordinances of the kingdom. Beneath his jeweled throne, with a thousand officials arrayed, from towering Mount E songs of longevity rise. Across fields vast as Lake Dongting, music harmonizing yin and yang resounds. He sports in the Palace of Immortals, soaring beyond the clouds and rain. The mountains and streams manifest extraordinary auspicious signs; jade and silk tributes flow without cease.

    This humble servant, blessed to be born in an age of peace, has had fortune to meet a sage who knows the times. My humble name has been inscribed in the Golden Registry; my steps have reached the Jade Pool. Though not in Yao's ancient court, I have been permitted to join the assembly where all beasts dance. All scholars of Zhou might sing the verse: "Even the youngest can achieve." With sincere devotion turned toward the sun, I humbly offer this benediction for ten thousand years.
  footnotes:
    - The 'purple egg' refers to Silla's legendary founding—the sacred egg from which the founder emerged, symbolizing the heavenly mandate.
    - The Four Youths (Hwarang) were the elite warrior-scholar caste of Silla, embodying both martial prowess and spiritual refinement.
    - The 'Golden Registry' and 'Jade Pool' are Daoist concepts representing divine recognition and immortal status.
    - This poem celebrates the establishment of the Palgwanhoe (Eight-View Festival), attributing its origins to Silla's Hwarang spirit and positioning it as renewal of ancient celestial rites under the new Joseon dynasty.
